<br>
I was making a point about creating a 'safe' space for roleplaying.  That's all.  I was drawing a comparison to the gay, feminist, and minority communities' experiences with 'safe' space because that's what I have experience with.<br>
<br>
I was *NOT* drawing a one-for-one parallel between being gay and being a roleplayer.  Of course the experience of being queer is different than the experience of being a roleplayer.  Believe me, I was a queer teen, and I deal with LGBT teens on a daily basis.  I'm aware of the studies, and I'm aware of the issues and problems that arise.<br>
<br>
Further, I never said I held to the opinion that straight people don't belong in gay bars.  In fact, if you parse my statement there accurately, I said there are gay people who think that, but I did not say I was one of those people.  Likewise, I have never said that &quot;powergamers&quot; (etc) don't belong on our server.<br>
<br>
Nor did I even say a word about &quot;powergamers&quot;.  Not one.  <br>
<br>
My question was how do we keep this server a viable space for roleplaying?  At what point does our server just turn into simply a 'special rules' server, where the community itself is more or less identical to the communities on the blue servers?<br>
